  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with ribeye versus filet mignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Ribeye's higher fat content and marbling calls for bigger, more tannic wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo to cut through the richness. Filet mignon's leaner, more delicate texture pairs beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or Merlot that won't overpower the subtle beef flavors. The cooking method also matters—a heavily charred ribeye can handle bolder wines than a gently pan-seared filet.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at room temperature with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red wines should be served slightly cooler than typical room temperature—around 60-65°F (15-18°C)—to best complement steak. This temperature allows the wine's tannins to integrate smoothly with the meat's proteins while preserving the wine's aromatic complexity. Wines served too warm can taste flabby and overly alcoholic, competing rather than complementing your perfectly cooked steak.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is ignoring the sauce and preparation method, focusing only on the cut of meat. A delicate filet with béarnaise sauce needs a different wine than the same cut with a bold peppercorn crust. Additionally, many people choose wines that are too light for grilled or blackened steaks, where the char and smoky flavors require wines with sufficient structure and intensity to match.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair white wine with steak successfully?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, but choose full-bodied, oak-aged white wines like aged Chardonnay, white Rhône blends, or Viognier. These wines work particularly well with lighter preparations like herb-crusted filet mignon or steak with cream-based sauces. The key is matching the wine's weight and intensity to the dish—a buttery Chardonnay can beautifully complement a steak with mushroom cream sauce where a light Sauvignon Blanc would be overwhelmed.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good budget-friendly wines that pair well with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Portuguese Douro reds, Argentine Malbec, or Spanish Tempranillo—these offer excellent structure and bold flavors at reasonable prices. Côtes du Rhône and Washington State Cabernet blends also provide great value for steak pairings. These wines typically range from $12-25 and offer the tannin structure and flavor intensity needed to complement beef without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose wine for different steak doneness levels?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rare to medium-rare steaks pair best with wines that have softer tannins and elegant structure, like Burgundy or Sangiovese, which complement the meat's natural flavors. Well-done steaks require wines with more robust tannins and higher intensity—think Cabernet Sauvignon or Syrah—to match the more concentrated, caramelized flavors that develop with longer cooking. The key is matching the wine's power to the steak's intensity level.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is aged wine necessary for steak pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Not necessarily—many young, well-structured wines pair excellently with steak and may even be preferable for certain preparations. Young wines often have more vibrant fruit flavors and firmer tannins that can complement grilled or seasoned steaks beautifully. However, aged wines bring complexity and softer tannins that work wonderfully with simply prepared, high-quality cuts where you want the wine's nuanced flavors to shine alongside the beef.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine regions produce the best steak pairing wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux, Napa Valley, and Barolo are classic regions known for wines that excel with steak due to their structured tannins and bold flavors. However, don't overlook regions like Mendoza (Argentina), Stellenbosch (South Africa), and Australia's Coonawarra, which produce excellent value wines specifically suited to red meat. These regions' warm climates and specific terroir create wines with the concentration and structure that make ideal steak companions.</p>
